      },
      "output": "The sky appears blue due to a phenomenon called **Rayleigh scattering**. Here is the step-by-step breakdown of how it works:\n\n### 1. Sunlight is a Spectrum\nAlthough sunlight looks white, it is actually made up of all the colors of the rainbow (red, orange, yellow, green, blue, indigo, and violet). Light travels as waves, and each color has a different wavelength:\n*   **Red light** has long, lazy waves.\n*   **Blue and violet light** have much shorter, choppier waves.\n\n### 2. The Atmosphere is an Obstacle Course\nEarth's atmosphere is filled with gases (mostly nitrogen and oxygen) and tiny particles. When sunlight hits these gas molecules, the light is scattered in different directions.\n\n### 3. Short Waves Scatter More\nBecause blue light travels in shorter, smaller waves, it strikes the gas molecules and gets scattered much more easily than red light. Imagine throwing large rocks and small marbles into a forest; the marbles are going to bounce off the trees and fly everywhere, while the big rocks might punch through or travel further in one direction.\n\nBecause the blue light is bouncing around in every direction, when you look up, your eyes are catching that scattered blue light coming from every part of the sky.\n\n### Why isn't the sky violet?\nViolet light has an even shorter wavelength than blue light, so technically, it scatters even more. However, the sky doesn't look violet for two reasons:\n1.  **The Sun's Output:** The Sun emits much more blue light than violet light.\n2.  **Human Vision:** Human eyes are much more sensitive to blue than violet. Our brains interpret the mix of scattered colors primarily as pale blue.\n\n### What about Sunsets?\nWhen the sun is setting, the light has to travel through much more of the atmosphere to reach your eyes because it is at a low angle. By the time the light gets to you, the blue light has been scattered away completely, leaving only the long-wavelength colors\u2014**reds, oranges, and pinks**\u2014to pass through.",
